data.name: delayTime
data.description: once fully loaded, delay final rendering of our page by this amount of miliseconds,  		so any async scripts can finish firing. 		default = 0.  min=0, max = 300000 		RECOMENDED: don't use this, use injectedScripts instead, and set the window['pjsc_meta'].remainingTasks to zero when ready to finish.

data.name: geolocation
data.description: specify what region you want your page-request to be processed in.  use the 'Query Geolocations" API to determine valid choices.  default=null (anywhere)

data.name: injectedScripts
data.description: string or array of strings.  specify custom scripts you wish to include into your page once the page is fully loaded (or once postDomTimeout occurs) This lets you parse/process the dom, manipulate the page, etc. You may input either a single script (string) or an array of scripts (string array). arrays of scripts are loaded and executeed in-order, waiting for the previous to complete execution before starting the load of the next. Note that if your page times out (request.timeout) then any remaining scripts will be aborted. Default = [] === SCRIPT OUTPUT === your script may output to the window['pjsc_output'] variable, and that will be returned to you via the response.injectedScriptOutput variable. this response.injectedScriptOutput is a normal javascript object, so complex data can be sent back to you as JSON. If you have multiple scripts being injected, a best-practice is to have each script store it's output to it's own variable, for example: myScript.js ==> response.injectedScriptOutput.myScript === SCRIPT INPUT === the "window['pjsc_meta'].pageResponse" variable. this contains a copy of the entire pageResponse (including the .request) from immediatly before the injectedScripts started being loaded. This lets you read information about the current page, plus gain access to any custom data you may put in request.requestId === DELAY PAGE RENDER === if your injectedScript wishes to delay the page render for any reason, you may set the window['pjsc_meta'].remainingTasks number to greater than zero. This will cause the page to not render until the value becomes zero again. (up to the maximum time specified by your request.timeout variable) This is useful if you are waiting on AJAX calls. if you want your script to generate data to be returned to you, write to the window['pjsc_output'] variable. this will be used to populate pageResponse.injectedScriptOutput. === DELAY SCRIPT EXECUTION === if you specify request.delayTime, your injectedScripts run after this completes. however, remember that request.timeout is a hard-limit, aborting any page that takes longer than this.

data.name: isDebug
data.description: if true, we will return extra debug info in the pageResponse.serviceMetadata. default=false

data.name: loadImages
data.description: you should only set this to TRUE if rendering jpeg (where the visuals matter), 	otherwise you will need to wait for extra useless data default=false

data.name: outputAsJson
data.description: set to true to output results as JSON, which will provide additional metadata about the page render. 	Note that this is the required for calls to the batch API but optional for the single-request API.  default=false

data.name: pdfPaperSize
data.description: used only if .type==="pdf" default= { format: 'A4', orientation: 'portrait', border: '1cm' }

data.name: postDomLoadedTimeout
data.description: after the domLoad event triggers, wait up to this amount more before returning (if page-load doesnt finish before then) . value in ms. default 2500

data.name: requestId
data.description: string or json.  use as a 'tracking tag' value you can specify that will be sent back with the page render results. useful for passing external info about a page render.  Also useful for passing data to injected scripts.

data.name: requestType
data.description: required: 'text', 'jpeg', 'png', 'pdf', 'script', or 'raw'.  		raw:  will output using the headers returned from the page's server.  		jpeg: will take a screenshot. 'text' will return the page content with Mime type of text.  		script: will return only the contents of your page window['pjsc_output'] variable.   see request.injectedScripts for details on how to set this

data.name: resourceUrlBlacklist
data.description: by default, we blacklist .css files. 	you should only set this to "[]" if rendering jpeg/pdf/png (where the visuals matter), 	otherwise you will need to wait for extra useless data.  for optimial performance, we recommend also blocking 3rd party stuff like facebook-social and google analytics.  default=['.*\.css.*']

data.name: resourceUrlWhitelist
data.description: used to allow resources that would otherwise be blacklisted. default=[]

data.name: targetUrl
data.description: the url you wish to render. 	Client-side and server-side redirects will be respected. 	Set the 'isDebug' and output as JSON to view redirect and resource load information.

data.name: timeout
data.description: if the page load does not complete before this time, stop and return what you have.   		default = 15 sec (15000). max value is 5 minutes (300000), min is 1sec (1000)

data.name: userAgent
data.description: you can set a custom useragent here. default = = 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/28.0.1468.0 Safari/537.36 PhantomJsCloud.com'
data.value: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/28.0.1468.0 Safari/537.36 PhantomJsCloud.com

data.description: set the size of the viewport. good for changing the rendering of responsive sites. also useful for force-loading infinite-scroll AJAX elements. Size in pixels. Default is null (not set). example option is 1280x720

description:
Do you need to screen-scrape Javascript Websites? 

PhantomJs.Cloud is 
- A web-browser hosted as a service, using Chrome WebKit to render your javascript heavy webpages as HTML, JPEG, PDF, or JSON.
- A Cloud of PhantomJS instances to process more than 100 pages per second.
- A REST API allowing you to request and obtain your pages.
